Description: CVE-2026-54369 - Fix symlink-related TOCTOU/follow vulnerability in libacl
 The pathname-based libacl entry points acl_get_file(), acl_set_file(),
 acl_extended_file() and acl_delete_def_file() resolved the supplied path
 separately for each underlying syscall (getxattr/setxattr/removexattr/
 stat). A local attacker who controls any component of the path could
 swap a symlink between calls and redirect ACL read/write operations to
 an arbitrary file, enabling unauthorized ACL manipulation and local
 privilege escalation.
 .
 This is a targeted backport of the libacl portion of upstream commit
 5906d28 ("Add libacl _at function variants", acl v2.4.0). Rather than
 introducing the new acl_get_file_at/acl_set_file_at/acl_extended_file_at/
 acl_delete_def_file_at exported symbols (which would require a new
 ACL_1.3 symbol-version block and a libtool LT_CURRENT/LT_AGE bump and
 therefore an ABI break for bullseye's libacl1), the symlink-safe path
 resolution is inlined directly into the existing four exported
 functions:
 .
   1. open(path, O_PATH | O_NOFOLLOW | O_CLOEXEC) atomically resolves
      the path without following a final-component symlink.
   2. fstat() on the resulting fd plus an S_ISLNK() check rejects
      symlinks with ENOTSUP.
 3. All subsequent xattr/stat operations use /proc/self/fd/N (which
    the kernel resolves through the fd table) so the same inode is
    operated on for every step, eliminating the path-based TOCTOU.
 .
 No new exported symbols are added, no symbol-version map / .ver file
 is bumped, the libacl1 SONAME is preserved, and only the four .c files
 in libacl/ are modified.
 .
 Backport adaptation: acl_get_file() now returns ENOTSUP for symlinks.
 getfacl already handles this by falling back to mode-bit ACLs, so
 test/misc.test is updated to match the new symlink behaviour.
Origin: backport, https://cgit.git.savannah.nongnu.org/cgit/acl.git/commit/?id=5906d2868ec8d3b08be556153696e6b1122eeeda
Author: Root.io Patch Platoon <patches@root.io>
Last-Update: 2026-06-30
